according to San Francisco in the 1930s, originally published in 1940. This would surely come as a surprise to the millions who know and love the Golden Gate Bridge or recognize the Transamerica Building’s pyramid. This invaluable Depression-era guide to San Francisco relates the city’s history from the vantage point of the 1930s, describing its culture and highlighting the important tourist attractions of the time. David Kipen’s lively introduction revisits the city’s literary heritage—from Bret Harte to Kenneth Rexroth, Jade Snow Wong, and Allen Ginsberg—as well as its most famous landmarks and historic buildings. This rich and evocative volume, resonant with portraits of neighborhoods and districts, allows us a unique opportunity to travel back in time and savor the City by the Bay as it used to be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  a1930s.  aallen ginsberg.  aamericana.  abay area.  abret harte.  acalifornia history.  acalifornia.  acity life.  acoast.  afamous landmarks.  agolden gate bridge.  agreat depression.  ahistoric buildings.  ainterwar period.  ajade snow wong.  akenneth rexroth.  anonfiction.  apolitics.  asan francisco history.  asan francisco.  atransamerica building.  atravel.  aunited states.  aurban.  awpa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026880740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094887740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948877423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520948877/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alle